\f2\b\fs36 Class Description
\b0 \

\fs16 \

\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\f0\fs28\li2100\fc0\cf0 This is a MutableArray class where every object that's beeing added gets stored at the correct place. The insertion is done via binary insertion, so that it might be a bit of a overhead for small arrays. The purpose of this class is to get an easy and fast implementation for priority lists and such.\
\
Per definition the methods 
\b - addObjectAtIndex
\b0 : and such, do not work as the name suggests; the objects added are stored at the correct place to keep the array sorted.\
\
As an example you can try:\
\

\f3\fs24 SortedArray *mySortedArray;\
\
mySortedArray = [SortedArray arrayWithObjects:@"3",@"5",@"1",@"-1",nil];\
NSLog(@"mySortedArray contains %@",[mySortedArray description]);
\f0\fs28 \
\

\pard\fs16\li1360\fc0\cf0 \

\pard\tx6140\fs28\fi-4040\li6140\fc0\cf0 All methods of the NSMutableArray class are implemented and work as supposed.\
\
\

\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\f2\b\fs36\li1360\fc0\cf0 Known Bugs\

\b0\fs16 \

\f0\fs28\li2100 None.\
\
Be aware that the sortedArray might get corrupt when used by multiple threads that keep changing the values of the objects inside the sortedArray.\
